<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-11-14T23:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-11-14T23:30:00-05:00" n="133" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d133">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">501.A Summaries/11–1449:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United
                                    Nations</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Austin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg></opener>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-11-14T23:30:00-05:00">November 14, 1949—11:30 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1342.</p>
                            <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                            <p rend="center">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chinese Case</hi>
                            </p>
                            <p>After carefully reading the US-suggested resolution in the Chinese
                                case, <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> President Romulo” said that
                                he could go along with the ideas expressed therein. He thought he
                                would like to join in sponsoring such a proposal should that action
                                become desirable, but said he would have to obtain the instructions
                                of his Government.</p>
                            <p>Rau (India) promised to consider the possibilities of co-sponsorship
                                of such a proposal.</p>
                            <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Austin</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>